The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
		 Monday, April 12, 2004  Q amp;A				 Demat dilemma
																																																																																													Is it mandatory to have a demat account for buying and selling shares?																																																																																													If there is a transfer of shares at the end of a fiscal, then who is entitled to receive the dividend for that year, the transferor or the transferee?																																																																													Madhabi D Ghosh, Calcutta 
																																																																																													Nowadays, it is mandatory and convenient to have a demat account for buying and selling shares since hardly any shares are available in the physical form.																																																																																													The person whose name appears in the books of the company as on the record date of the dividend will be entitled to receive the dividend amount. If the process of transfer is complete by that record date, then the transferee will receive the dividend, if not, then the transferor will receive it.																																					Retired rebate																																																																																															I am retired and my source of income is interest received from various investments, which amounts to Rs 1,50,000 per annum. Can I get income tax rebate by investing the amount in various tax-saving instruments and what is the maximum rebate?																																																																													D Mohanty, Rourkela
																																																																																													You can get tax rebate by investing in various tax-saving instruments and the maximum amount of rebate that you can get is 20 per cent of your investment amount.																																					Varistha Bima																																																																																															Is the pension from LIC Varistha Bima Yojana taxable?																																																																													Somnath De, Dhanbad
																																																																																													The pension received from LIC Varistha Bima Yojana is taxable. The tax payable will depend on the income and the tax bracket of the pensioner.																																					Gratuity gain																																																																																															Is gratuity received on retirement a taxable income?																																																																													 K Bose, Jamshedpur
																																																																																													For government employees, gratuity is fully exempt from income tax. For non-government employees covered by the Gratuity Act, the minimum of the following will be exempted: actual gratuity received or Rs 3,50,000 or 15 days salary for each completed year of service (calculated as salary last drawn multiplied by 15/26). For others, the minimum of the following will be exempted: actual gratuity received or Rs 3,50,000 or half months average salary for each completed year of service.												If you have any queries about investing or taxes or a high-cost purchase you are planning, mail to: btgraphabpmail.com, or write to: Business Telegraph, 6 Prafulla Sarkar Street, Calcutta 700 001
